ph_descripcion:
Photos by @Andy_Best | The first Milky Way of 2023: The center of our galaxy rises just before the sun does this time of year. As the moon waned, it rose morning by morning, blocking out the core. Also in the mix is the rising sun, which leaves only 15 minutes of visibility before the gigantic band of stars dissipates in the morning light.

As the days go on, the galaxy's core will rise earlier and earlier, leaving us with a fantastic Milky Way "season"—one that I love to run around capturing right before the sunrise each glorious day.

Get out there!
ph_atributos: Photo by National Geographic Adventure on March 05, 2023. May be an image of nature and sky.

ph_descripcion: Photo by @katieorlinsky | A trail is left after a sled dog team crossed Eagle Summit in the interior of Alaska. This is among the most difficult sections of the thousand-mile Yukon Quest international sled dog race, one of the toughest sporting events on the planet. Up to 50 professional sled dog teams journey in February through the subarctic North American wilderness, along what was once the Klondike Highway, a historic route that sled dog teams used to deliver mail during the gold rush at the turn of the 20th century. Temperatures during the race reach as low as minus 58° Fahrenheit (-50°C) and winds can be up to 50 miles (80 km) an hour. Visibility can be nonexistent, and it is so far north that sunlight lasts for only a few hours a day. I covered the race for National Geographic in 2015 and made this image after huffing and puffing through waist-deep snow to the summit to photograph the lead dog team. Instead I overshot the trail, gave up on finding the team, relaxed, and photographed the stars.

Photo by @praveenjayakaran | I was on a trip to South Africa where I met @dalesteyn, a former professional cricketer often regarded as one of the greatest fast bowlers of all time. When we decided to take a break after work to go surfing at Jeffreys Bay, I captured Dale Steyn riding the waves on a longboard and having some fun. Jeffreys Bay is a beautiful and very popular beach for surfing. I wish I could return during the Open J-Bay surfing competition and witness the pros surfing the big waves.
#surf #southafrica #longboardsurfing #surfphotographer

Photos by @erinhogue | After claiming gold in Sochi, half-pipe Olympian @KaitlynFarr found out she has a spinal condition that puts her at high risk of becoming paralyzed. Because of this, she was told by doctors never to snowboard again. “Well, that simply was not an option,” said Kaitlyn Farrington. After doing a ton of research and talking to numerous specialists, she learned that as long as she didn’t leave the ground, she could still snowboard.

Here she is at Mount Baker in Washington, leaning into a perfect turn.

ph_descripcion: Photo by Corey Rich @coreyrichproductions | This photograph of my good friend @jimmychin was captured when he, @chris__mcnamara, and I climbed Snake Dike on Half Dome in Yosemite National Park years ago. Despite having many cumulative decades of mountain experience among us, we still very nearly got into deep trouble that day. A thunderstorm had blown in from the west, and we suddenly found ourselves in the worst possible location: near the top of one of the tallest granite domes around, with lightning crashing all around us! We felt what seemed to be needles in our heads, and we saw sparks jumping from fingertips to our belay devices as we set up to rappel down as quickly as possible. That concerned expression on Jimmy’s face is dead serious. Though this is considered an "easy" rock climb, Snake Dike is a serious undertaking and a huge adventure.

ph_descripcion: Photo by @jason_gulley_science | Paddlers and inner tubers drift through the confluence of Florida’s tannin-stained Santa Fe River and the clear spring water flowing from the Devil’s Spring System, which discharges around 80 million gallons of fresh groundwater to the surface every day. ph_descripcion:
Photos by @donaldmiralle | The Eddie Aikau Big Wave Invitational is the Super Bowl of surfing—run only 10 times since 1985, as it requires consistent wave heights of over 20 feet with good conditions.

Everything lined up Sunday, January 22, 2023, after the buoys to the north of Oahu showed the “Eddie swell” topping a massive 27.5 feet at 19 seconds, a swell that Hawaii hasn’t seen in decades for the Eddie. But from many accounts of veteran big-wave surfers who paddled out in Waimea Bay, it was one of the greatest surfing experiences they’ve ever had. Definitely nonstop the wildest Super Bowl of surfing I’ve covered.

It’s fitting—when Pat Curren passed away on January 22, the same date that Duke Kahanamoku did 55 years ago—that this was the biggest, most consistent Eddie ever run and that an on-duty Waimea lifeguard alternate invitee surfed in between shifts in the tower to win the Eddie Aikau Big Wave Invitational.

After collecting his check and being hoisted on the shoulders of other surfers he grew up with on the North Shore, he got back into the lifeguard stand to finish his shift so “everyone gets home safe.” Congrats #LukeSheparson (pictured on his winning wave in his final heat with the rainbow in photos 1 and 7). Eddie would be proud.

The 10th Eddie also marked the first time women have surfed in the same heats as men. Watching the Wahine and Kane paddling out in maxed-out Waimea was an amazing part of surfing history to witness.

#eddieaikau #waimeabay #eddiewouldgo #bigwavesurfing #eddieswell #bigwaveinvitational

ph_descripcion: Photo by @jason_gulley_science // Divers and paddlers explore the crystalline clear water of Little River Spring in Branford, Florida. Every day, billions of gallons of cool, refreshing groundwater bubble to Florida’s surface through more than a thousand springs, making the state’s concentration of springs one of the largest in the world. Because many of Florida’s springs have a constant average temperature of about 72ºF (22ºC), they’re year-round playgrounds for accessible aquatic adventures, offering a pleasant retreat from the summer heat or a warm swimming hole when temperatures dip in winter. // From swimming in freshwater springs to paddling through mangroves and exploring hidden caverns, adventure awaits you in Florida. @visitflorida

ph_descripcion: Photo by Savannah Cummins @sav.cummins | Climbers on the exposed summit ridge of Broad Peak, in Pakistan. Broad Peak is the 12th highest mountain in the world, sitting at 8,051 meters, or 26,414 feet. It is often considered one of the "easiest" 8,000-meter peaks, but "easy" and "8,000-meter" don't fit well together. Speckled with cornices, loose rock, and ice, Broad Peak's hazardous summit ridge is more than a mile long. This makes for one of the longest summit days of all the 8,000-meter peaks.
ph_atributos: Photo by National Geographic Adventure on December 22, 2022.

Photo by @nikkik_smith // The Good-Looking One in Hyalite Canyon near Bozeman, Montana, draws ice climbers to push themselves. One of the hallmarks of climbing ice is that it is constantly growing or shrinking. No season's formation is the same. Wanting to add a little more adventure to a climb he had been on before, Alan Rousseau decided on a less trafficked variation and followed a series of ice blobs on the left of the route before joining the main ice flow toward the top. This area includes the ancestral lands of the Apsáalooke (Crow) Nation, Confederated Salish and Kootenai Tribes (Flathead Nation), Tséstho’e (Cheyenne), Niitsítpiis-stahkoii (Blackfoot/Niitsítapi), and Shoshone-Bannock Tribes. // When you dare to explore the unfamiliar, you feel more alive. ph_descripcion: Photo by @grant_gunderson // The seemingly endless backcountry surrounding Mount Baker in Washington State is a winter enthusiast’s dream. ph_descripcion: Photos by @donaldmiralle | More than 150 cyclists, including 27 with permanent physical challenges—blind people, above- and below-knee amputees, and wheelchair handcyclists—rode for 7 days and nearly 640 miles, from San Francisco to San Diego, to raise over $1.8 million for the @cafoundation. The money will help thousands of young athletes with physical challenges gain access to sports worldwide. This annual bike ride has earned a reputation as one of the premier events in the country where individuals can use their passion for cycling to make a difference in the lives of others.

ph_descripcion: Photo by @sofia_jaramillo5 | Franny Weikert cruises down a descent while bike-packing a route, called A Swell Night Out, through the San Rafael Swell Recreation Area in southeastern Utah. For three days, we biked along the swell, a distinct geological area permeated by sharp, sudden upthrusts of rock that formed 70 to 40 million years ago. Geologic features from the Permian to Cretaceous periods, native endangered plants such as the San Rafael cactus, and Native American pictographs and petroglyphs can all be seen in this unique area. #utah #geology #bikepacking

ph_descripcion: Photo by @Andy_Best | If you look closely, you can see my little family walking along the beach. We were enjoying a remote part of the Baja, Mexico, coastline with nothing but sand and ocean for 80 miles on either side of us. At low tide you can find small cave features and rock formations covered with crabs. The little ones get a kick out of seeing them while running around the outcroppings looking for tidewater creatures. The stars, too, are off the charts out here. Even with no moon, the stars cast a shadow across the sand. Absolute bliss. For more stories, please visit @Andy_Best.

ph_descripcion: Photos by Irene Yee @ladylockoff // When we hear the word “desert,” we usually think of a seemingly barren place that’s devoid of water and life, but life here actually adapts and thrives despite difficult conditions. Chef Melissa King and I got to experience this environment in two different ways. First, we met up with Amanda Egertson, stewardship director for the Deschutes Land Trust, who encouraged us to be still in the middle of a desert trail, allowing us to see a host of insects and butterflies come alive. Afterward, Melissa and I embarked on her first outdoor rock climb to experience the high Oregon desert in a grand way. Feeling inspired by this landscape, Melissa made us a meal of dumplings and tea, over which we continued to discuss the many connections between humans and nature. // The #MazdaCX50 is purpose-built to connect you with nature. After all, it’s on unpaved dirt and gravel paths where our sense of wonder comes alive. The first-ever Mazda CX-50. We’re more human in nature.
ph_atributos: Photo by National Geographic Adventure on October 28, 2022.

Photo by @Andy_Best | Alaska has been a trip years in the making for me. There are many reasons: the giant mountains, the vast swaths of nothing but spruce and bogs for as far as the eye can see, and of course, the northern lights. Even though it rained all summer while I was shooting some projects, I managed to drive a few hundred miles to find clear skies for this night. The storm was immense, and I was running around in the dark giggling like a little kid in a candy store. If you haven't seen the northern lights, I highly recommend you do.
For more, please follow me @Andy_Best.

ph_descripcion: Photo by @coreyrichproductions // Luke Reberšak enjoys a mellow midsummer paddle on the Savinja River. Photo by Sofia Jaramillo @sofia_jaramillo5 | Bill Dores flies over the Sawtooth Range near Stanley, Idaho. The mountains are part of the Sawtooth National Recreation Area (SNRA), established nearly 50 years ago by Congress as part of the Sawtooth National Recreation Act. The SNRA is made up of more than 750,000 acres of protected land, including wilderness areas, dozens of 10,000-foot-tall peaks, and countless recreation activities. Flying over the area at sunset made me appreciate the size of the area, which is about as large as Rhode Island.
For more images from Idaho and the Rockies, follow @sofia_jaramillo5.

ph_descripcion: Photo by @chrisburkard | While most people avoid volcanic eruptions, a brave few go straight to the heart of them. Pictured here are members of the Icelandic Association for Search and Rescue securing the area to ensure safety, ready to help as needed during the recent activity in southern Iceland. On August 3, the Meradalir eruption brought lava to the surface of the region for the first time since September 2021. Despite warnings from the Icelandic Meteorological Office, which urged locals and tourists to stay away from the volcano, many couldn't resist the fascination of the bright orange lava flows. People went up close to snap photos, fly drones, and just take in the once-in-a-lifetime chance of seeing an active volcanic eruption.
ph_atributos: Photo by National Geographic Adventure on August 05, 2022.

ph_descripcion: Photo by @MikeOlbinski | I've been chasing dust storms (or haboobs, as they're also known) across the state of Arizona for over a decade. I never expected to see one of this caliber during tornado season, but that's exactly what happened on May 18, 2022. The central plains of the United States were suffering from a bad drought, and dust storms had been popping up all over. On this day, strong storms merged into a fast-moving shelf cloud that picked up dust along the way, creating a spectacular haboob that I was thankful to witness, in Johnson City, Kansas.

ph_descripcion: Photo by @MikeOlbinski | Lightning is probably my favorite thing to chase, but on occasion, it can feel as though it's doing the chasing. This fast-moving, severe storm near Dalhart, Texas, earlier this spring was just that kind of beast. It seems rare to see a storm that's throwing out so many cloud-to-ground lightning strikes every few seconds, and when I get lucky enough to be on a storm like that, I generally celebrate! This was scary, though, and while my cameras did the work, I was safely inside the truck. This bolt landed only about a quarter mile away, extending out from the storm, so that the image gives you an almost three-dimensional appreciation of the strike.
ph_atributos: Photo by National Geographic Adventure on July 08, 2022.

ph_descripcion: Photo by @katieorlinsky | Alaskan wilderness guide Michael Wald pack-rafts the Alatna River in Gates of the Arctic National Park, Alaska. In 2018 National Geographic writer @craigwelch and I accompanied ecologist Ken Tape and Michael Wald along 64 miles of the Alatna as they looked for signs of the ecological impact of beavers in the Arctic. Beavers are among a number of animal species moving north as a result of warming weather and climate change, and they have the unique ability to singlehandedly transform the landscape in irreversible ways. Scientists like Ken Tape are working to understand what this means for the future.

ph_descripcion: Photo by @cliford.mervil // I’ve always loved being outdoors. More specifically, I’ve always felt at home in the mountains. Returning to these North Carolina gems is always like returning home to me—to a place where I can grow and connect to the beautiful land I live on, forming memories that will last a lifetime. // This National Get Outdoors Day, @visitnc and experience firsts that turn into moments you'll never forget. It's incredible to take my little family all over the continent—including to this part of the Mojave Desert, in Nevada—with me as I work.
